article on bitcoin mining got basic factual errors wrong my favorite by there is one kinghit takedown that i think weve all neglected it turns out that the entire conceptual underpinning for the entire nytimes piece is fatally flawed specifically, nytimes used a type of emission calculation called marginal emissions accounting, which doesnt actually work in reality kind of a big problem the marginal emissions model doesnt work because it is does not model how grids actually work it is as if whoever created it had never talked to a grid operator quite possible the consequence is that it will generate horribly overestimated emission calculations for any electrical user you try to calculate emissions for heres how the model works marginal emissions assumes that grid operators maximize for costeffectiveness of electricity, stepping through a sequence of steps from cheapest renewable to most expensive fossil fuel electricity generation er, no thats not how grid operators work youd cause blackouts and be fired if you did that grid operators optimise for stability first, with costeffectiveness of supply being a close second for this reason, grid operators will first establish reliable baseload energy sources this will typically mean prioritizing nonintermittent energy sources hydro, nuclear, gas, coal once a high percentage of baseload is established, then intermittent power sources can progressively be prioritized wind, solar im simplifying a very complex multivariable decisionmaking strategy, but this simplification is more accurate than the fundamentally wrong assumption that grid operators have the liberty to select power generation based purely on price without considering stability what this means is that marginal emission accounting will invariably hideously overestimate the impact of adding any new electrical user to the grid because of its flaws, the perfect methodology to use if you want to overstate the actual emissions of a particular group of electrical users want to make out that evs are evil no problem, run some marginal emission accounting magic numbers on them, and itll show that they use over 90 fossil fuel want to make out that nytimes offices are emitting huge quantities of carbon no problem, run marginal emission accounting over their usage want to run a hitpiece on bitcoin mining in a mainstream newspaper no problem, run marginal emission accounting over their usage what the nytimes article proves about bitcoin emissions is nothing, other than a how spurious a metric marginal emissions accounting is, in the real world b how easily a badfaith actor with wide reach can easily influence mainstream opinion by manipulating facts and using concdeptually flawed methodologies footnote i traced the origins of the marginal emissions model it came from an academic paper written in 2017 which makes 64 mentions of electricity cost, but takes no account of grid stability into its analysis instead, there is a single footnote which acknowledges exceptions to this rule exist when transmission and minimum generation constraints prevent least cost dispatch the problem is, this is not a mere exception, it is the norm that price is a secondary consideration to stability thats why ercot is called ercot energy reliability council of texas, not elctctgbocaccot the energy letscrashthegridbyonlycaringaboutcost council of texas this footnote blows up the model its like declaring to customs im carrying nothing dangerous in my baggage other than the nuclear weapons in my carryon
